ed and egalitarian, Carib societies are rife with tension and difference; but this imbalance conditions social dynamism and a distinctive mode of cohesion. The Imbalance of Power is based on the author’s fieldwork in partnership with Vanessa Grotti, who is working on a companion volume entitled Living with the Enemy: First Contacts and the Making of Christian Bodies in Amazonia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAkurio Indians. 0aGroup identityzGuiana. 0aLeadershipzGuiana. 0aMasculinityxPolitical aspectszGuiana. 0aPower (Social sciences)zGuiana. 0aTrio Indians. 0aWayana Indians. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aamazonia.  aamerican indian.  aamerindian politics.  aamerindian.  acarib.  acultural anthropology.  acultural studies.  adefying stereotypes.  adifferences between tribes.  aegalitarian.  aegalitarianism.  aethnographic.  aeurope.  aeuropean polity.  afeminism.  afeminist.  aguiana.  aharmonious with nature.  ahistory.  aindian stereotypes.  aindigenous people.  anative american.  apatriarchy.  apolitical ideologies.  asocial dynamic.  asociology.  astate of nature.  atension.  aunconventional.  aunited states history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311099822140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781785333101?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781785333101423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781785333101/original  a978-3-11-099822-1  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK